    {
      "gridPos": {"h": 18, "w": 24, "x": 0, "y": 65},
      "id": 12,
      "options": {
        "code": {"language": "plaintext", "showLineNumbers": false, "showMiniMap": false},
        "content": "## Is Talos Misconfigured? Quick Diagnostic Checklist\n\nThis dashboard surfaces metrics. For Talos-side config that isn't currently metric-scraped, run these `talosctl` checks. Filed under [TALOS-fa7](https://github.com/TheBranchDriftCatalyst/talos-homelab) (observability epic) is the broader goal of making these into proper metrics.\n\n### 1. Kernel panic behavior (the #1 cause of our 'meltdowns' on 2026-05-29)\n```sh\nfor ip in 192.168.1.54 192.168.1.177 192.168.1.144 192.168.1.30 192.168.1.19; do\n  echo \"--- $ip ---\"\n  talosctl --nodes $ip read /proc/sys/kernel/panic_on_oops    # should be 1 (auto-reboot) OR 0 (just log)\n  talosctl --nodes $ip read /proc/sys/kernel/panic            # reboot delay after panic (sec)\ndone\n```\nDefault: `panic_on_oops=1, panic=10`. If you want to debug WITHOUT auto-reboot, set `panic_on_oops=0` (kernel logs the oops instead of rebooting). Talos doesn't expose this in machineconfig; need a `--extra-kernel-args` patch.\n\n### 2. KubePrism health (per-node apiserver proxy)\n```sh\nfor ip in 192.168.1.54 192.168.1.177 192.168.1.144 192.168.1.30 192.168.1.19; do\n  echo \"--- $ip ---\"\n  talosctl --nodes $ip get kubeprismstatuses\ndone\n```\nExpected: `HOST=127.0.0.1:7445, HEALTHY=true` on every node. If unhealthy → Cilium and apid can't talk to apiserver properly.\n\n### 3. Talos service health\n```sh\ntalosctl --nodes 192.168.1.54 service\n```\nAll services should show `STATE=Running, HEALTH=OK`. apid, etcd, kubelet, machined, trustd are critical.\n\n### 4. etcd backend health (control plane)\n```sh\ntalosctl --nodes 192.168.1.54 etcd status\ntalosctl --nodes 192.168.1.54 etcd alarm list  # should be empty\n```\n\n### 5. conntrack table pressure (high values → service routing fails silently)\n```sh\nfor ip in 192.168.1.54 192.168.1.177 192.168.1.144 192.168.1.30 192.168.1.19; do\n  echo -n \"$ip: \"\n  count=$(talosctl --nodes $ip read /proc/sys/net/netfilter/nf_conntrack_count)\n  max=$(talosctl --nodes $ip read /proc/sys/net/netfilter/nf_conntrack_max)\n  echo \"$count / $max\"\ndone\n```\nAlert if any node is >80% full.\n\n### 6. Cilium agent BPF map pressure\n```sh\nkubectl exec -n kube-system <cilium-pod> -- cilium-dbg map list --verbose | head -30\nkubectl exec -n kube-system <cilium-pod> -- cilium-dbg metrics list | grep -E 'bpf_map_pressure|policy_count'\n```\n\n### 7. Capture script (when kubectl is dead)\n```sh\n./scripts/capture-meltdown-evidence.sh\n# Writes to .output/incidents/<UTC-timestamp>/ — see post-mortem doc\n```\n\n### Common misconfiguration sources\n- **`allowSchedulingOnControlPlanes: true`** combined with single CP → workload pressure on CP makes meltdowns worse. Mitigate via HA (TALOS-arx).\n- **Cilium `kubeProxyReplacement: true` on single CP** → cilium-agent restart on CP breaks all host networking (chicken-and-egg). KubePrism helps but doesn't fully fix.\n- **`failurePolicy: Fail` admission webhooks pointing at unhealthy operators** → cluster-wide pod admission stalls. Set Ignore (TALOS-9cf).\n- **etcd snapshot CronJob hitting single etcd member** → fsync storm during snapshot (initially suspected but not confirmed).\n- **Cilium memory limit too low** for the workload (Hubble buffer, SPIRE, etc.) → OOM kills agent. We bumped 1Gi → 2Gi.\n\n### After this dashboard says everything is fine but you're still seeing issues:\n1. Run capture-meltdown-evidence.sh BEFORE rebooting next time\n2. Read `/var/log/kernel-capture/<node>.log` directly via talosctl after a reboot — kernel ring buffer captured pre-panic\n3. Check Loki `{job=\"kernel-capture\"}` for any panic patterns in the last 24h\n4. Verify the Mimir push from alloy-node isn't timing out (we saw `context deadline exceeded` to mimir-nginx — separate issue)",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "title": "Talos Configuration Debug Runbook",
      "transparent": false,
      "type": "text"
    }
